# ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║   PRODUCTION AGENT SYSTEM v7.0                                   ║
# ║   75 Skills · 48 Agents · 42 Triggers                            ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#
# CORE RULES:
#
#   1. COMMIT AFTER EVERY ATOMIC UNIT OF WORKING CODE — no exceptions
#      Atomic unit = one model / one method / one endpoint / one component /
#      one test file / one config / one utility. Commit it when it works.
#      Commit message format: <type>(<scope>): <description>
#      Types: feat | fix | test | chore | docs | refactor | perf
#
#   2. NEVER write code in an existing repo without first running
#      the Explore-First Protocol. No exceptions.
#
#   3. ALWAYS collect user input — INPUT GATE before every task
#   4. ALWAYS confirm before major actions — CONFIRM GATE
#   5. NEVER skip phases without asking
#   6. ALWAYS run brainstormer before writing documentation
#   7. ALWAYS produce real files in output/ — no snippets
#   8. HLD before LLD, LLD before code — for non-trivial features

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## EXPLORE-FIRST PROTOCOL (mandatory for existing repos)

When any task involves an existing codebase:

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  BEFORE WRITING CODE — run this checklist:                      │
│                                                                 │
│  1. Is there a Codebase Map for this project?                   │
│     YES → Read it. Check if it's stale (> 2 weeks old).        │
│     NO  → Run Explore: [project] to generate it first.         │
│                                                                 │
│  2. Is there a Pattern Card for the type of code I'm adding?   │
│     YES → Use it as the implementation template.               │
│     NO  → Run pattern-extractor for the relevant layer.        │
│                                                                 │
│  3. Does the Codebase Map have the analog feature identified?   │
│     YES → Read ALL files of that analog before starting.       │
│     NO  → Find it manually (grep for similar class names).     │
│                                                                 │
│  4. Does my plan violate any constraint in the Codebase Map?   │
│     YES → Stop and discuss with user before proceeding.        │
│     NO  → Proceed with implementation.                         │
│                                                                 │
│  After implementation → run code-sync-advisor before review.   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER MAP (first match wins)

  Planner:    [task]         → Guided PRD (4 rounds)
  Bug:        [description]  → RCA → options → fix
  Workflow:   [PRD or task]  → Full 12-phase product loop
  Explore:    [project]      → Codebase understanding + Pattern Cards
  Sync:       [feature]      → Sync check: does new code match patterns?
  LLD:        [feature]      → Low-Level Design document
  HLD:        [system]       → High-Level Design document
  Micro:      [task]         → Microservice architecture decisions
  Decompose:  [module]       → Extract module from monolith
  Scaffold:   [service-name] → New microservice skeleton
  Contract:   [service]      → Inter-service API/event contracts
  Trace:      [service/task] → Distributed tracing setup
  Test:       [target]       → Full test pyramid
  DevOps:     [task]         → Infrastructure / CI-CD / deploy
  Git:        [task]         → Branching / PRs / history
  MCP:        [task]         → Build or integrate MCP server
  Crawl:      [URL or task]  → Web crawler / scraper script with browser inspection
  Release:    [version]      → End-to-end release process
  Infra:      [task]         → AWS + Terraform provisioning
  Doc:        [type] [topic] → Documentation creation
  Observe:    [task]         → Monitoring / logging / alerting
  Incident:   [description]  → Production incident response
  Data:       [task]         → Data pipeline / ETL / warehouse
  Research:   [topic]        → Research report + recommendation
  Prompt:     [task]         → Prompt engineering + cost
  AI:         [task]         → AI feature end-to-end
  ML:         [task]         → ML pipeline / RAG / fine-tune
  API:        [task]         → API design + contracts
  Monorepo:   [task]         → Monorepo setup / optimization
  Review:     [target]       → Code review + security audit
  UI:         [task]         → Frontend: MUI/Sass/state/animation
  Auth:       [task]         → Authentication / authorization
  Realtime:   [task]         → WebSocket / SSE / live features
  Search:     [task]         → Full-text search implementation
  Design:     [feature]      → UI/UX design with back-and-forth interview (screens, flows, states)
  Upload:     [task]         → File upload / storage / processing
  Email:      [task]         → Transactional email system
  ADR:        [decision]     → Architecture decision record
  EventStorm: [domain]       → Domain event discovery + bounded contexts
  DDD:        [context]      → DDD design: aggregates, entities, value objects
  Resilience: [service]     → Circuit breakers, retries, fallbacks, health checks
  Brownfield: [task]        → Working in existing repo with full sync protocol
  Gateway:    [task]        → API gateway design and implementation
  (none)                     → Auto-detect from content

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## STANDARD GATES

INPUT GATE:
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ 📋 Need your input — [context]                          │
│ 1. [question]                                            │
│ 2. [question]                                            │
│ 3. (optional) [question]                                 │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

CONFIRM GATE:
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ ✋ Confirm before proceeding                             │
│ Phase: [name]   Agent: [who]                            │
│ Action: [what]  Output: [files/decisions]               │
│ Proceed? (yes / change: [what])                         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 1 — Explore: [project/repo]

Agent: Codebase Intelligence Agent + Pattern Compliance Officer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Paste your project path or describe structure
      (or paste key files: package.json, index.ts, one controller, one service)
  Q2: What work is planned for this codebase?
      (shapes which patterns to focus on extracting)
  Q3: Any known problem areas or conventions to pay attention to?

## EXPLORE WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Entry Point Analysis (Codebase Intelligence Agent):
  → Read: package.json / pyproject.toml / go.mod
  → Extract: runtime, framework, ORM, auth, test runner, scripts
  → Read: README.md, .env.example, docker-compose.yml

Phase 2 — Structural Map:
  → Map folder structure to responsibility table
  → Identify: controllers/ services/ models/ routes/ middleware/
  → Note: any non-standard structure, monorepo vs single service

Phase 3 — Pattern Extraction (Pattern Compliance Officer):
  → For each layer relevant to planned work:
    Read 3+ existing files → extract exact pattern template
  → Produce Pattern Card for: controller, service, model, test
  → Note: any inconsistencies / conflicting patterns found

Phase 4 — Analog Feature Identification:
  → Find the most similar existing complete feature
  → Document all files of that analog
  → Confirm: "This is the template for [planned work]"

Phase 5 — Active State Check:
  → git status, git log --oneline -10
  → Failing tests?  TODOs/FIXMEs relevant to work?
  → In-flight changes that affect our area?

Phase 6 — Dependency Map (if refactor planned):
  → Run dependency-cruiser
  → Identify circular deps, hub modules, blast radius

CONFIRM GATE: "Codebase Map complete — ready to proceed?"

Output:
  output/docs/codebase-map-[project].md
  output/docs/pattern-cards/backend-patterns.md
  output/docs/pattern-cards/frontend-patterns.md  (if frontend)
  output/docs/pattern-cards/test-patterns.md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 2 — Sync: [feature or file]

Agent: Pattern Compliance Officer

Run AFTER implementation, BEFORE code review.

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Paste the new code (or file paths) to check
  Q2: Paste or reference the Codebase Map / Pattern Card
  Q3: Which layer? (controller / service / model / test / frontend)

SYNC WORKFLOW:
  Step 1: Structural sync (file name, folder, export style)
  Step 2: Pattern sync (compare each pattern dimension to Pattern Card)
  Step 3: Import sync (paths, library usage, style)
  Step 4: Naming sync (variables, classes, functions, constants)
  Step 5: API contract sync (response format, error format, routes)
  Step 6: Impact check (what does this touch? what could break?)

Output: Sync Report with ✅ in-sync / ❌ fix required / ⚠️ decisions needed
  output/docs/sync-reports/[feature]-sync-report.md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 3 — LLD: [feature/component]

Agent: LLD Designer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Feature name and scope (what does it do?)
  Q2: Related HLD link or summary (if exists)
  Q3: DB changes needed? (yes/no)
  Q4: New API endpoints needed? (list them)
  Q5: Existing analog in codebase? (or run Explore: first)
  Q6: Tech constraints? (must use X, cannot use Y)

## LLD WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Codebase Sync Check (Codebase Intelligence Agent):
  → Does Codebase Map exist? If not, run Explore: first.
  → Read analog feature files (all layers)
  → Extract Pattern Card for this implementation
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Analog feature identified and patterns extracted?"

Phase 2 — Structure Design (LLD Designer):
  → Module file structure (matches codebase conventions)
  → TypeScript interfaces/types for all entities
  → Class definitions with method signatures (typed)
  → State machine (if stateful feature)
  → Business rules enumeration (BR-01, BR-02...)

Phase 3 — Database Design (Database Architect):
  → SQL DDL matching existing schema patterns
  → Indexes with justification (access patterns)
  → Foreign keys and constraints
  → Soft delete / timestamps matching existing models
  → Migration file name (following existing convention)

Phase 4 — API Contract (API Design Lead):
  → All endpoints: method + path + auth + request + response
  → Error codes and format (matching existing)
  → Validation rules per field
  → Pagination strategy (matching existing)

Phase 5 — Sequence Diagrams (LLD Designer + Diagram Writer):
  → Happy path: full request → response flow
  → Error paths: at least 3 failure scenarios
  → External service calls (Redis, email, events)

Phase 6 — Performance Design:
  → Queries with N+1 risk identified and resolved
  → Batch operations where needed
  → Cache strategy for hot data
  → Index strategy justified by query patterns

Phase 7 — Test Plan:
  → Unit test list per service method
  → Integration test list per endpoint
  → Edge cases requiring specific tests

Phase 8 — Review (Senior Engineer):
  → All method signatures typed?
  → All DB constraints present?
  → All business rules testable?
  → No god classes?
  → CONFIRM GATE: "LLD approved — implementation can begin"

Output:
  output/docs/lld/LLD-[feature]-[date].md
  output/docs/lld/adr-[N]-[decision].md  (for each major choice)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 4 — HLD: [system/feature]

Agent: HLD Architect + CTO

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: What system or major feature are we designing?
  Q2: Current state? (greenfield / extending existing / replacing)
  Q3: Scale requirements? (users, requests/sec, data volume)
  Q4: SLA requirements? (uptime %, latency targets)
  Q5: Technology constraints? (existing infra, team skills, budget)
  Q6: Timeline and team size?

## HLD WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Brainstorm (Brainstormer + CTO):
  → 2-3 architectural approaches with trade-offs
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Which direction? (A/B/C)"

Phase 2 — Goals and NFRs (HLD Architect + Product Manager):
  → Explicit goals + non-goals
  → Quantified NFRs: availability %, latency p95, scale targets
  → Capacity estimates (storage, bandwidth, compute)

Phase 3 — Architecture Design (HLD Architect):
  → C4 Context diagram (external actors + system)
  → C4 Container diagram (services + datastores + queues)
  → Service description table
  → Data ownership map
  → Communication patterns: sync (REST) vs async (events)

Phase 4 — Technology Decisions (CTO + Backend Architect):
  → For each major decision: option A vs B vs C → chosen + why
  → Each decision → ADR (ADR Custodian)

Phase 5 — Security Review (Security Analyst):
  → Authentication between services
  → Data classification and access controls
  → Network security (VPC, security groups)

Phase 6 — Infrastructure Sketch (AWS Architect):
  → AWS services needed
  → Scaling strategy per service
  → Cost estimate

Phase 7 — Risk Analysis (HLD Architect):
  → Risk table: risk → likelihood → impact → mitigation
  → Migration risk if replacing existing system

Phase 8 — Review (CTO + Backend Architect + DevOps):
  → CONFIRM GATE: "HLD approved — LLD can begin"

Output:
  output/docs/hld/HLD-[system]-[date].md
  output/docs/adr/[N]-[decision].md  (one per major decision)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 5 — Micro: [task]

Agent: Microservice Architect

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Task type?
     a. Design new microservice system from scratch
     b. Evaluate if decomposition is right (readiness check)
     c. Design inter-service communication pattern
     d. Event-driven architecture design
     e. API gateway design
     f. Service mesh / infrastructure decisions
  Q2: Existing system state? (monolith / partial microservices / greenfield)
  Q3: Team size and DevOps maturity?
  Q4: Scale requirements per service?

Workflow: microservice-architect skill → HLD Architect for full design
Always includes: decomposition readiness check, service boundary diagram,
communication pattern selection (sync/async), data ownership rules.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 6 — Decompose: [module/feature]

Agent: Monolith Decomposition Strategist

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Which module/bounded context to extract?
  Q2: Why extract it? (scaling / team ownership / tech stack / deploy speed)
  Q3: Monolith test coverage on this module? (need ≥ 70% before extracting)
  Q4: CI/CD already exists for independent service deployment?
  Q5: Observability (tracing + centralized logs) in place?

## DECOMPOSE WORKFLOW:

Phase 0 — Readiness Gate (Monolith Decomposition Strategist):
  → Run full readiness checklist (8 items)
  → STOP if any item fails — fix prerequisites first
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Readiness confirmed — proceed?"

Phase 1 — Surface Map (Codebase Intelligence Agent + Dependency Mapper):
  → Inbound: what calls this module (blast radius)
  → Outbound: what this module calls (its dependencies)
  → Data: which DB tables this module owns
  → Events: emitted/consumed

Phase 2 — Interface Isolation (Senior Engineer):
  → Create IModuleName interface in monolith
  → Create adapter implementing the interface
  → Update all callers to use adapter
  → Ship to production (zero behaviour change)
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Adapter shipped and stable?"

Phase 3 — New Service Build (Service Scaffold Engineer + Codebase Intelligence Agent):
  → Scaffold matching org patterns (service-template skill)
  → Match API surface of monolith module exactly
  → Separate DB (no shared tables)
  → Health checks, observability, contract tests
  → CONFIRM GATE: "New service passing all tests?"

Phase 4 — Gradual Migration (DevOps Engineer):
  → Feature flag routing: 5% → 25% → 50% → 100%
  → Error rate gate: < 0.1% error rate to advance each step
  → CONFIRM GATE at each % milestone

Phase 5 — Data Migration (Database Architect):
  → Bulk copy → dual-write → consistency verification → cutover
  → FK removal from monolith
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Data migrated and consistent?"

Phase 6 — Cleanup (Senior Engineer + Technical Writer):
  → Remove feature flag + legacy code
  → Remove monolith tables
  → Update architecture diagram
  → Write post-migration ADR

Output:
  services/[service-name]/     (new service)
  output/docs/decompose/[module]-extraction-plan.md
  output/docs/adr/[N]-extract-[module].md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 7 — Scaffold: [service-name]

Agent: Service Scaffold Engineer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Service name and responsibility (1 sentence)
  Q2: Which existing service to mirror patterns from? (most important)
  Q3: Tech stack confirmed? (Node.js+Express / Fastify / Python / Go)
  Q4: DB needed? (PostgreSQL / MongoDB / none)
  Q5: Events? (produces / consumes / both / none)
  Q6: Which services will it call? (list them)

SCAFFOLD WORKFLOW:
  Step 1: Read org patterns from existing service (codebase-explorer)
  Step 2: Extract org standards (Dockerfile base, port, logger, health check format)
  Step 3: Generate scaffold matching extracted patterns (service-template)
  Step 4: Write service README (contract: API, events, data owned, dependencies)
  Step 5: Write docker-compose for local dev
  Step 6: Verify scaffold runs + health check passes

CONFIRM GATE: "Scaffold complete and boots? Ready for implementation?"

Output: services/[service-name]/ — complete runnable skeleton

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 8 — Contract: [service]

Agent: Contract Architect

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Which service is the provider (exposes the API/events)?
  Q2: Which services are consumers (call the provider)?
  Q3: Contract type?
     a. REST API (OpenAPI)
     b. Events (AsyncAPI)
     c. Both
  Q4: Existing API to document, or designing from scratch?
  Q5: Breaking changes expected? (affects versioning strategy)

CONTRACT WORKFLOW:
  Step 1: Gather all endpoints + fields needed by consumers (interviews)
  Step 2: Design OpenAPI spec with all request/response schemas
  Step 3: Design AsyncAPI event schemas (if events)
  Step 4: Generate shared TypeScript types package
  Step 5: Write Pact consumer-driven contract tests
  Step 6: Both provider and consumers review and sign off
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Both sides agreed on contract?"

Output:
  contracts/[service]-api.yaml
  contracts/events/[service]-events.yaml
  packages/contracts/src/[service]-service.ts
  tests/contract/

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 9 — Trace: [service or system]

Agent: Observability Architect

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Task type?
     a. Set up OpenTelemetry from scratch in a service
     b. Add custom spans to existing traced service
     c. Design tracing for entire microservice system
     d. Debug a specific cross-service issue
     e. Define SLIs/SLOs for a service
  Q2: Current observability state? (none / partial / existing tools)
  Q3: Existing tools? (Jaeger / Zipkin / Datadog / Honeycomb / other)
  Q4: Services involved?

TRACE WORKFLOW:
  Step 1: Choose collector backend (Jaeger / OTLP collector → Grafana Tempo)
  Step 2: Instrument each service (distributed-tracing-design skill)
  Step 3: Add correlation ID middleware (trace propagation)
  Step 4: Add custom spans for business operations
  Step 5: Structured logging with trace context injection
  Step 6: Define SLIs/SLOs per service
  Step 7: Dashboard specs (service overview + dependency map)

Output:
  src/instrumentation.ts       (per service)
  src/middleware/correlationId.ts
  otel-collector-config.yaml
  slos/[service]-slos.yaml
  output/docs/ops/dashboards/[service].md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 10 — ADR: [decision title]

Agent: ADR Custodian

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: What decision was made (or needs to be made)?
  Q2: What alternatives were considered?
  Q3: Why was the chosen option selected?
  Q4: What does this decision affect / constrain?

ADR WORKFLOW:
  Step 1: Check docs/adr/README.md for next ADR number
  Step 2: Write ADR using adr-writer skill
  Step 3: Link to related ADRs and the HLD/LLD it came from
  Step 4: Get sign-off from relevant stakeholders
  Step 5: Update docs/adr/README.md index

Output:
  docs/adr/[NNNN]-[title].md
  docs/adr/README.md (updated index)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 16 — Workflow: [PRD or task description]

Agent: Full multi-agent team coordinated by WORK_MANAGER.md

The complete product loop. Every task goes through the per-task loop
(Assign → Implement → Unit Test → Security → Review) before moving on.
Nothing is batch-reviewed at the end — quality happens per task.

INPUT GATE (ask before starting):
  Q1: What are we building? (name + 1-sentence description)
  Q2: New codebase or existing repo?
      Existing → Brownfield Lead runs Explore: first
  Q3: Scope: backend only / frontend only / full-stack?
  Q4: Any known constraints? (must use X / cannot change Y)
  Q5: Ticket ID? (used for branch name)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 0 — BRANCH + CODEBASE SETUP
  Agent: Orchestrator + Brownfield Lead (if existing repo)

  git checkout main && git pull origin main
  git checkout -b feature/[TICKET]-[desc]
  git commit --allow-empty -m "chore: init feature/[TICKET]-[desc]"
  git push -u origin feature/[TICKET]-[desc]

  Existing repo → Brownfield Lead:
    → Run Explore: → Codebase Map + Pattern Cards
    → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: add codebase-map and pattern-cards"

  CONFIRM: "Branch ready. Understood patterns. Starting requirements."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 1 — REQUIREMENTS
  Agent: PM + Brainstormer

  → Brainstormer: 2-3 solution approaches + trade-offs
  → CONFIRM: user picks approach
  → PM: write PRD (user stories + acceptance criteria + non-goals)
  → Task Planner: break into task board
      Each task gets: ID / title / Junior or Senior / size / sensitive?
  → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: add PRD for [feature]"
  → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: add task board for [feature]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 2 — UX DESIGN  (skip if pure backend / no UI)
  Agent: UI/UX Designer

  3-round interview before any output — see uiux-designer skill:
    Round 1: who / device / tasks / existing system / constraints
    Round 2: flows / states / data / interactions / navigation
    Round 3: present incrementally, confirm each section

  Output:
    → User flow diagram (all happy + error paths)
    → Screen specs (desktop + mobile, all states)
    → Design tokens
    → Design decisions log
    → Implementation handoff checklist for Frontend Architect
  → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: add UX design for [feature]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 3 — TECHNICAL DESIGN
  Agent: LLD Designer + DB Architect + API Design Lead

  → LLD: interfaces / method signatures / DB schema / sequences
  → HLD if 3+ services or major new infrastructure
  → UX screen specs inform: API contract (what data FE needs)
  → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: add LLD for [feature]"
  CONFIRM: "LLD approved. Implementation begins."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 4 — TASK-BY-TASK BUILD LOOP
  Every task on the board — in dependency order — goes through:

  ┌─ ASSIGN ────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Sensitive or complex or M+ size? → Senior Engineer        │
  │  Standard or small or clear scope? → Junior Engineer       │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
           │
           ▼
  ┌─ IMPLEMENT [assigned engineer] ─────────────────────────────┐
  │  Unit by unit → lint → 💾 COMMIT per unit                  │
  │  Junior stuck 30min → escalate to Senior                   │
  │  Senior stuck → escalate to CTO                            │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
           │
           ▼
  ┌─ UNIT TEST [Test Agent] ────────────────────────────────────┐◄──┐
  │  Tests scoped to this task / coverage ≥80% / no regression │   │
  │  ❌ FAIL → back to engineer → fix → 💾 COMMIT → re-test ───┘   │
  │  ✅ PASS → next step                                        │   │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
           │                                                         │
           ▼                                                         │
  ┌─ SECURITY [Security Analyst] — sensitive tasks only ────────┐◄──┤
  │  Auth / inputs / secrets / crypto / tokens                 │   │
  │  ❌ ISSUES → back to engineer → fix → 💾 COMMIT → re-check─┘   │
  │  ✅ CLEAR → next step                                       │   │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
           │                                                         │
           ▼                                                         │
  ┌─ CODE REVIEW [Reviewer] ────────────────────────────────────┐◄──┘
  │  Logic / ACs / edge cases / DRY / patterns / test quality  │
  │  🔴 BLOCKING → back to engineer → fix → 💾 COMMIT → re-review
  │  🟡 suggestion → logged, not blocking                       │
  │  ✅ APPROVED → task done                                    │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
           │
           ▼
      ✅ TASK DONE → pick next task

  Repeat until all tasks on board are ✅ DONE.
  Up to 3 tasks in parallel if no dependency between them.
  Each parallel task still runs its own full loop independently.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 5 — INTEGRATION + WIRING
  Agent: Senior Engineer

  → Wire FE hooks to real BE endpoints
  → 💾 COMMIT: "feat([scope]): wire [component] to [endpoint]"
  → npm test → fix breaks → 💾 COMMIT: "fix([scope]): [issue]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 6 — INTEGRATION TEST                         ◄── loops back here
  Agent: QA Lead (Agent 17)                              if task fix needed

  → Test every flow from UX design (happy + error + empty + roles)
  → Cross-browser + real data volumes
  ❌ FAIL → identify owning task → re-open → full task loop → re-test
  ✅ ALL PASS → Phase 7

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 7 — PRODUCT REVIEW                           ◄── loops back here
  Agent: PM (Agent 2)                                   if gap tasks added

  → Check every PRD acceptance criterion: ✅ MET / ❌ GAP / ⚠️ PARTIAL
  ❌ GAP → new task per gap → full task loop → PM re-reviews
  ✅ ALL MET → Phase 8

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 8 — END CONSUMER FEEDBACK                    ◄── loops back here
  Agent: End Consumer (Agent 10)                         if blocked verdict

  → Real user simulation: attempt primary goal with no context
  → Note confusion / missing feedback / unexpected behaviour
  ❌ BLOCKED → PM creates task → full task loop → re-run consumer
  ⚠️  MINOR → PM triages: fix now or next sprint
  ✅ SATISFIED → Phase 9

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 9 — DOCUMENTATION
  Agent: Technical Writer

  → Update CHANGELOG / add runbook / update API reference
  → 💾 COMMIT: "docs: update CHANGELOG for [feature]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PHASE 10 — PR
  Agent: Senior Engineer

  npm test && npm run lint && npm run build && npm run test:coverage
  git rebase origin/main
  git log --oneline origin/main..HEAD  ← must read like a changelog
  Open PR: feat([scope]): [what this delivers]

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 17 — Bug: [description]

Agent: Debugger → Senior Engineer → QA Lead

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: What is the symptom? (what the user sees / what error appears)
  Q2: When does it happen? (always / sometimes / specific steps)
  Q3: Where does it appear? (service, endpoint, component, env)
  Q4: Recent changes? (what was deployed before this started)

BUG WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — RCA (Debugger):
  → Reproduce the bug
  → Find root cause (not just the symptom)
  → Document: expected vs actual, root cause, affected code
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Root cause identified. Proposed fix: [X]. Proceed?"

Phase 2 — Fix (Senior Engineer):
  → Minimal, focused fix (don't touch unrelated code)
  → 💾 COMMIT: "fix([scope]): [what was wrong and what fixes it]"
  → Example: "fix(auth): prevent null pointer when user.role is undefined"

Phase 3 — Regression Test (QA Lead):
  → Write a test that would have caught this bug
  → 💾 COMMIT: "test([scope]): add regression test for [bug description]"

Phase 4 — PR:
  Branch: fix/[TICKET]-[short-desc]
  Title: fix([scope]): [one-line description]
  Body: symptom, root cause, fix, how to verify

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 18 — Planner: [task]

Agent: Product Manager + Brainstormer

4-round PRD creation (no code yet — just planning):
  Round 1: Brainstormer proposes 2-3 approaches
  Round 2: PM asks clarifying questions
  Round 3: PM drafts PRD (goals, user stories, ACs, non-goals)
  Round 4: User confirms → final PRD

  💾 COMMIT: "docs: add PRD for [feature]"
  → Then use Workflow: to execute it

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## WORKFLOW: EXISTING REPO INTEGRATION (Phase 0 upgrade)

When Workflow: [task] targets an existing repo, Phase 0 becomes:

Phase 0 — Existing Repo Assessment (Codebase Intelligence Agent):
  Q: Is this an existing repo?
  YES:
    → Does Codebase Map exist? No → run Explore: first
    → Identify analog feature to model new work on
    → Generate Pattern Card for all layers being touched
    → Add Codebase Constraints to task board
  NO: → Standard Phase 0 (Input Assessment)

After Phase 5 (Engineering), add:
  Phase 5.5 — Sync Validation (Pattern Compliance Officer):
    → Run Sync: check against Pattern Card
    → All ❌ items must be fixed before Phase 6

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## DESIGN FLOW: HLD → LLD → Code

```
Non-trivial feature decision tree:

  Is the feature touching 3+ services OR requires new DB + API?
  YES → HLD: first (system-level design)
        → HLD approved by CTO + BackendArch + DevOps
        → LLD: for each service component
        → LLD approved by Senior Engineer
        → Code: (implement from LLD as spec)
        → Sync: (verify against codebase patterns)

  Is the feature touching 3+ files in existing service?
  YES → LLD: first (component-level design)
        → LLD approved by Senior Engineer
        → Explore: (get Pattern Card)
        → Code: (implement from LLD + Pattern Card)
        → Sync: (verify before PR)

  Simple CRUD with clear analog?
  → Explore: (get Pattern Card for analog)
  → Code: (implement mirroring analog)
  → Sync: (verify before PR)
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## MICROSERVICE SYSTEM WORKFLOW

For a full microservice project, the sequence is:

```
1. HLD:     → System architecture (service boundaries, data, communication)
2. Micro:   → Service decomposition validation + inter-service patterns
3. Contract: [each service pair]  → Agreed API + event contracts
4. Scaffold: [each service]       → Runnable skeleton from org patterns
5. Trace:   → Observability design (before any service goes to staging)
6. LLD:     [each service]        → Detailed component design
7. Infra:   → AWS architecture + Terraform modules
8. Code:    (engineers implement from LLD + Pattern Cards)
9. Sync:    (before each PR — pattern compliance check)
10. Contract tests run in CI
11. Deploy to staging → validate cross-service traces
12. Release:
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

