## TRIGGER 11 — EventStorm: [domain]

Agent: DDD Architect

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Domain or system to storm (e.g. "e-commerce checkout", "SaaS subscription")
  Q2: Source: domain expert interview / existing codebase / both?
  Q3: Goal: discover service boundaries / design new feature / understand existing system?
  Q4: Scope: full domain or specific sub-domain?

## EVENTSTORM WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Domain Events (DDD Architect + Brainstormer):
  → event-storming skill: Phase 1-2 (chaotic exploration + temporal ordering)
  → Capture ALL domain events in past tense
  → Arrange in timeline
  → CONFIRM GATE: "All events captured?"

Phase 2 — Commands + Actors:
  → For each event: who/what triggered it?
  → Map: Actor → Command → Event
  → Add policies (when X → automatically do Y)
  → Identify external systems

Phase 3 — Aggregate Discovery:
  → Group events around "things" that hold state
  → Define invariants per aggregate
  → Draw state machines for stateful aggregates

Phase 4 — Bounded Context Mapping:
  → Cluster aggregates by linguistic boundary + ownership
  → Name each context (use business language)
  → Map context relationships (ACL, customer/supplier, conformist)
  → Document hot spots 🔴

Phase 5 — Output Integration:
  → Context map → feed into HLD: / Micro:
  → Aggregates → feed into LLD:
  → Hot spots → become ADR: decisions
  → Domain events → feed into Contract: (AsyncAPI)

Output:
  output/docs/hld/event-storm-[domain]-[date].md
  output/docs/hld/context-map-[domain].md
  output/docs/adr/ (one per hot-spot decision)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 12 — DDD: [bounded context]

Agent: DDD Architect + Senior Engineer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Which bounded context to design? (from EventStorm output or describe)
  Q2: Task type?
     a. Design aggregates, entities, value objects from scratch
     b. Refactor existing code to DDD structure
     c. Add domain event publishing to existing aggregates
     d. Design repository interfaces for existing data layer
  Q3: Existing codebase? → run Explore: first
  Q4: Existing domain model? (paste or describe)

## DDD WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Ubiquitous Language (DDD Architect):
  → Glossary: 10-20 terms, domain expert definitions
  → Identify same-word-different-meaning conflicts (context boundaries)

Phase 2 — Aggregate Design (DDD Architect):
  → domain-driven-design skill: entities + value objects + aggregates
  → Invariants listed per aggregate
  → State machines for stateful aggregates
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Aggregate design approved?"

Phase 3 — Domain Events (DDD Architect):
  → Event schema per aggregate state transition
  → Domain events (internal) vs Integration events (external contract)
  → Event publishing hooks in aggregate methods

Phase 4 — Repository Interfaces (Senior Engineer):
  → Interface per aggregate root (domain layer — no DB knowledge)
  → Infrastructure implementation (Sequelize/TypeORM/Prisma)
  → Mapper: domain ↔ DB row

Phase 5 — Folder Structure (Senior Engineer):
  → Implement DDD layered structure: domain/ application/ infrastructure/
  → Ensure domain layer has ZERO infrastructure imports

Phase 6 — Codebase Sync (Brownfield Lead, if existing repo):
  → Does new DDD structure fit existing project conventions?
  → Migrate incrementally? Or new bounded-context module?

Output:
  src/[context]/domain/
  src/[context]/application/
  src/[context]/infrastructure/
  output/docs/lld/ddd-[context]-[date].md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 13 — Resilience: [service]

Agent: Resilience Engineer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Which service(s) to add resilience to?
  Q2: What are its external dependencies?
     (other services / external APIs / DB / cache / message broker)
  Q3: Current state? (no resilience / partial / needs review)
  Q4: Failure scenarios that have happened or are feared?
  Q5: Acceptable degraded behaviour per dependency?
     (e.g. "show cached price if pricing service is down")

## RESILIENCE WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Dependency Audit (Resilience Engineer):
  → List every outbound call this service makes
  → Classify each: critical (fail request) vs non-critical (degrade gracefully)
  → Current timeout? retry? circuit breaker? per dependency
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Dependency map complete?"

Phase 2 — Resilience Design (Resilience Engineer):
  → resilience-patterns skill
  → For each dependency:
    Timeout: [N]ms  Retry: [N] attempts, backoff [type]
    Circuit: threshold [N]%  reset [N]s
    Fallback: [strategy]
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Resilience design approved?"

Phase 3 — Implementation (Senior Engineer):
  → ResilientClient per downstream service
  → Circuit breakers with Prometheus/CloudWatch metrics
  → Health check /health/ready includes all dependencies

Phase 4 — Testing (QA Lead):
  → Chaos test: simulate each dependency failing
  → Verify circuit opens, fallback activates, errors don't cascade
  → Performance test: resilience overhead < 5ms at p99

Output:
  src/lib/resilientClients/[service]Client.ts
  src/routes/health.routes.ts (updated /health/ready)
  output/docs/ops/resilience-[service].md  (timeout/retry table)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 14 — Brownfield: [task]

Agent: Brownfield Lead (then hands off to appropriate engineer)

This trigger replaces manual Explore + Sync steps for ALL existing-repo tasks.
Think of it as: "I'm working in code that already exists — guide me."

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: What is the task? (add feature / fix bug / refactor / integrate)
  Q2: Paste or describe the relevant existing code (or file paths)
  Q3: How large is the change?
     XS: 1-2 files   S: 3-5 files   M: 6-15 files   L: 15+ files
  Q4: Existing Codebase Map? (yes/no/paste)
  Q5: Most similar existing feature in the codebase? (if known)

## BROWNFIELD WORKFLOW:

Phase 0 — Triage (Brownfield Lead):
  → brownfield-workflow skill: Phase 0
  → Classify change type and size
  → Determine: existing Codebase Map needed? LLD needed?

Phase 1 — Understand (Brownfield Lead + Codebase Intelligence Agent):
  → If no map: run Explore: workflow
  → If map exists: read relevant pattern cards
  → Find analog feature → read ALL its files

Phase 2 — Pattern Card (Brownfield Lead):
  → brownfield-workflow skill: Phase 2 — fill Pattern Card
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Patterns understood — proceed to design?"

Phase 3 — Design (proportional to size):
  XS/S: → Brownfield Lead sketches approach (method signatures + data flow)
  M:    → LLD: (codebase-aware) via LLD Designer
  L:    → HLD: + LLD: via HLD Architect + LLD Designer

Phase 4 — Implement (Senior/Junior Engineer):
  → Implement from Pattern Card + design
  → Every file matches Pattern Card conventions

Phase 5 — Sync Validation (Brownfield Lead):
  → Sync: workflow — check all 6 dimensions
  → Zero ❌ items before PR submission

Phase 6 — Test (QA Lead):
  → Tests follow test Pattern Card exactly
  → All pre-existing tests still pass

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 15 — Gateway: [task]

Agent: Backend Architect + Resilience Engineer

INPUT GATE:
  Q1: Task type?
     a. Design + implement new API gateway from scratch
     b. Add route/service to existing gateway
     c. BFF design (backend for frontend)
     d. Gateway resilience (circuit breakers, rate limits)
     e. Review existing gateway for gaps
  Q2: Client types? (web / mobile / partner API / internal services)
  Q3: Services to expose through gateway? (list them)
  Q4: Auth strategy? (JWT / API key / OAuth / per-route)
  Q5: Rate limit requirements? (per IP / per user / per endpoint)

## GATEWAY WORKFLOW:

Phase 1 — Design (Backend Architect + Brainstormer):
  → api-gateway-design skill
  → Gateway type: pass-through / aggregating / BFF
  → Route table: path → service → auth → rate limit
  → CONFIRM GATE: "Gateway design approved?"

Phase 2 — Resilience Design (Resilience Engineer):
  → Circuit breaker per downstream service
  → Timeout per route class (fast: 500ms, normal: 3s, slow: 10s)
  → Rate limit strategy per endpoint

Phase 3 — Implementation (Senior Engineer):
  → app.ts with full middleware stack
  → Correlation ID propagation
  → JWT validation + X-User-Id forwarding
  → Per-service circuit breakers
  → Health endpoint: /health/gateway

Phase 4 — Testing (QA Lead):
  → Route proxy tests
  → Auth enforcement tests (protected routes reject without token)
  → Rate limit tests (429 after limit exceeded)
  → Circuit breaker tests (503 when downstream circuit open)

Output:
  gateway/src/  — complete gateway implementation
  output/docs/tech/gateway-design.md

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## DESIGN FLOW: Full System → Code (updated v7)

```
New system with complex domain:
  EventStorm: → DDD: → HLD: → Micro: → Contract: → Scaffold: → Resilience: → LLD: → Brownfield: → Code → Sync:

New system without complex domain:
  HLD: → LLD: → Scaffold: → Resilience: → Code → Sync:

Existing repo, large feature:
  Brownfield: → LLD: (codebase-aware) → Code → Sync: → Review:

Existing repo, small feature:
  Brownfield: XS/S → Code (from Pattern Card) → Sync: → Review:

Microservice decomposition:
  EventStorm: → Micro: → Decompose: → Contract: → Scaffold: → Resilience: → Trace:

New microservice:
  EventStorm: (if domain unclear) → HLD: → DDD: → Contract: → Scaffold: → Resilience: → LLD: → Code → Sync:
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## NEW SKILLS (v7 additions)

Architecture:
  domain-driven-design      event-storming
  resilience-patterns       api-gateway-design
  brownfield-workflow

## AUTO-DETECT ADDITIONS (v7)

  event storm / bounded context / aggregate   → EventStorm:
  DDD / domain model / ubiquitous language    → DDD:
  circuit breaker / retry / bulkhead / resilience → Resilience:
  existing codebase / add to my project       → Brownfield:
  API gateway / BFF / backend for frontend    → Gateway:
  paste of existing code + "add X to this"   → Brownfield:

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 20 — Crawl: [URL or task description]

Agent: Crawler Agent (Agent 49)
Skills: crawler, mcp-builder, researcher

Writes production web crawling/scraping scripts.
ALWAYS opens the real URL before writing selectors.
ALWAYS asks questions before writing code.

AUTO-DETECT:
  "crawl / scrape / extract data from [site]"
  "get all [items] from [URL]"
  "monitor [site] for changes"
  "download [data] from [URL]"
  "automate browser to collect [data]"
  "build a scraper for [site]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

CRAWL WORKFLOW:

─── STEP 1 — INTERVIEW ROUND 1 ─────────────────────────────────────
Agent asks ALL of these before opening anything:

  1. What URL(s) to crawl?
  2. What data to extract? (list every field)
  3. Scope: one page / pagination / follow links / full site / URL list?
  4. How often will this run? (one-time / daily / scheduled)
  5. Output: JSON / CSV / database / console?
  6. Estimated volume? (~N pages / records)

  WAIT FOR ANSWERS.

─── STEP 2 — INTERVIEW ROUND 2 ─────────────────────────────────────
  7. Login required? → Yes: prompt creds interactively at runtime
  8. robots.txt restrictions? (agent checks when browser opens)
  9. Is content JS-rendered? (agent checks when browser opens)
  10. Error handling: retry recommended? Rate limit: N req/sec?
  11. Auth headers or cookies needed?

  WAIT FOR ANSWERS. Then summarise + CONFIRM before proceeding.

─── STEP 3 — OPEN URL IN CURSOR BROWSER ────────────────────────────
Agent opens the target URL to inspect real structure:

  □ GET https://[domain]/robots.txt → check allowed paths
  □ View page source → JS-rendered? YES → Playwright / NO → Cheerio
  □ DevTools → find CSS selectors for every field
  □ Find pagination selector + URL pattern
  □ Note: Cloudflare / CAPTCHA / anti-bot signals?
    → If blocked: inform user, do NOT attempt to bypass

  Agent presents findings:
  "I found these selectors — confirm before I write the script:
   [field]:  [selector]
   [field]:  [selector]
   Next page: [selector or URL pattern]
   Library:   Playwright (JS-rendered) / Cheerio (server-rendered)
   robots.txt: [allowed / disallowed path list]"

  WAIT FOR CONFIRMATION.

─── STEP 4 — WRITE CRAWLER ─────────────────────────────────────────
  → TypeScript, fully typed
  → CONFIG block at top (easy to change URL, output, rate limit)
  → Rate limiting (≥ 1s between requests — respect the server)
  → Retry with exponential backoff (3 attempts)
  → robots.txt check before crawling
  → Error handling: per-page failures logged, crawl continues
  → Pagination handled to completion
  → Output: JSON / CSV / DB per interview answers
  → Login: promptCredentials() at runtime if needed (never hardcoded)

  💾 COMMIT: "feat(crawler): add [target] crawler script"

─── STEP 5 — TEST ON 1 PAGE ─────────────────────────────────────────
  → Run against page 1 only
  → Show user the first 3-5 records:
    "Here's what was extracted from page 1:
     [record 1]
     [record 2]
     [record 3]
     Fields look correct? Any adjustments?"

  WAIT FOR CONFIRMATION before running full crawl.

─── STEP 6 — FULL RUN ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  → Run complete crawl (all pages / full scope)
  → Show: pages crawled / total records / errors / output file
  → If scheduled: add cron setup
  → 💾 COMMIT: "feat(crawler): add [target] full crawler with pagination"

─── CHECKLIST BEFORE DELIVERY ──────────────────────────────────────
  □ robots.txt checked and respected
  □ Rate limiting ≥ 1s between requests
  □ Retry with exponential backoff
  □ Per-page error handling (logs failure, continues)
  □ Output directory created if missing
  □ All fields extracted and typed
  □ Pagination handles last page / empty results
  □ Credentials from runtime prompt or env vars — never hardcoded
  □ Selectors confirmed against real page
  □ package.json with all dependencies
  □ Run instructions documented

─── HARD STOPS (never proceed if) ──────────────────────────────────
  ❌ Site has CAPTCHA → inform user: "This site uses CAPTCHA.
     I cannot bypass this. Consider: official API, data export,
     or contacting the site for data access."
  ❌ robots.txt disallows the path → inform user of restriction
  ❌ Site explicitly says "no scraping" in ToS → inform user
  ❌ Credentials need to be stored → use env vars, not source code

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## TRIGGER 19 — Design: [feature or screen name]

Agent: UI/UX Designer

The dedicated trigger for any UI/UX design work.
Uses multi-round back-and-forth interview before producing anything.
Never outputs a spec without completing all interview rounds.

AUTO-DETECT: trigger when user says:
  "design the [X]"
  "what should [X] look like"
  "create mockup for [X]"
  "wireframe [X]"
  "how should the UI work for [X]"
  "UI spec for [X]"
  "design the flow for [X]"
  OR: any Workflow: task where the feature has user-facing screens

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## DESIGN WORKFLOW (3-round interview before any output)

─── ROUND 1 — CONTEXT ──────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent asks these questions. All of them. In one message:

  📋 Before I design [feature], I need to understand the context.

  1. Who uses this? (admin / end user / both — and are they technical?)
  2. What device will they mostly use? (desktop / mobile / both equally)
  3. What are the 1-3 things they must be able to DO on this screen?
  4. Existing design system?
     → If yes: which library (MUI / Tailwind / custom)?
        Share a screenshot or describe an existing screen I should match.
     → If no: any apps/sites this should feel inspired by?
  5. What type of UI is this? (full page / modal / drawer / inline section / multi-step flow)
  6. Any hard constraints? (must be WCAG AA / must work on tablet / must fit sidebar)

  [Wait for answers — do NOT proceed to design]

After answers → summarise in 2-3 sentences:
  "So you need [X] for [user type] primarily on [device],
   designed to match [existing system or inspiration],
   that lets them [core tasks]. Is that right?
   Anything I misunderstood?"

[Wait for confirmation — do NOT proceed to design]

─── ROUND 2 — DEPTH (per screen) ───────────────────────────────────

Agent asks these questions for EACH screen in scope:

  📋 Now let's go screen by screen.

  For [Screen / Feature name]:

  FLOW:
  1. Walk me through the happy path.
     "The user arrives here because ___. Their first action is ___. Then ___."
  2. What are the 2-3 things users are most likely to get confused by or do wrong?
  3. What happens when they successfully complete the main action?
     (Stay on page / redirect to ___ / show toast / open next step)

  DATA:
  4. What data is shown on this screen? List every field.
  5. Is any data editable directly on this screen, or only in a separate form/modal?
  6. Rough scale: how many items/rows could this screen have?
     (< 20 items = show all / 20-200 = pagination / 200+ = search + pagination)

  STATES:
  7. What does this screen look like while data is loading?
  8. What if there's no data yet (first-time/empty state)?
  9. What errors can happen, and what should the user see?
  10. Are there different views for different user roles/permissions?

  INTERACTIONS:
  11. Can users select multiple items and do something to all of them?
  12. Any drag-and-drop, reordering, or inline editing?
  13. Any data that updates in real-time without the user refreshing?

  [Wait for answers — do NOT proceed to design]

If multiple screens, repeat these questions for each screen.

After answers → ask:
  "One more thing — how does the user navigate TO this screen?
   And how do they leave? (back button / breadcrumb / tab change / automatic redirect)"

[Wait for answer]

Then final confirmation:
  "Let me play back what I heard before I start designing:

   [Bulleted summary of every decision gathered in Rounds 1-2]

   Does this capture everything accurately?
   Any corrections or anything I missed before I start?"

[WAIT FOR EXPLICIT APPROVAL before producing any design output]

─── ROUND 3 — INCREMENTAL DESIGN OUTPUT ────────────────────────────

Present design in sections. After EACH section:
  → Present it
  → Ask: "Does this match your vision? Any changes?"
  → Wait for answer
  → Only proceed to next section after approval

Section A: User Flow
  → Text flow diagram showing all paths (happy path + error paths)
  → "Does this flow cover everything? Any missing paths?"

Section B: Screen layouts (one at a time)
  → Desktop ASCII wireframe (labeled, with dimensions noted)
  → Mobile ASCII wireframe (labeled)
  → "Does this layout work? Anything to add, remove, or rearrange?"

Section C: States per screen
  → Loading state description
  → Empty state (heading + subtext + CTA)
  → Error state (which errors, how shown)
  → Success state (toast / redirect / confirmation)
  → Any role/permission variants
  → "Do these states feel right? Any scenarios I haven't covered?"

Section D: Interactions
  → Table of: user action → system response → feedback shown
  → "Any interactions missing or wrong?"

Section E: Component hierarchy
  → Tree of components for each screen
  → Notes on which are new vs existing
  → "Any components I've missed or named wrong?"

Section F: Design tokens
  → Colors (primary, semantic, feedback)
  → Typography (sizes, weights, usage)
  → Spacing, radius, shadows
  → "Do these tokens match your brand? Any to change?"

Section G: Design decisions log
  → Every gap filled: what was missing → what was decided → why
  → "Any of these decisions you'd make differently?"

─── FINAL GATE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  "Design complete. Here's a summary of everything we decided:
   [Bulleted list of all key decisions]

   Ready to move to implementation?
   I'll hand off the spec to the Frontend Architect."

  💾 COMMIT: "docs: add UX flow diagram for [feature]"
  💾 COMMIT: "docs: add screen specs for [feature] (all states)"
  💾 COMMIT: "docs: add design tokens for [feature]"
  💾 COMMIT: "docs: add design decisions log for [feature]"

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## DESIGN RULES (apply everywhere, not just Design: trigger)

```
1. NEVER skip the interview. Every unasked question = a wrong design assumption.

2. NEVER dump the full spec at once. Present section by section. Confirm each.

3. ALWAYS design ALL states: loading / empty / error / success.
   A screen with only the "data loaded" state is an incomplete design.

4. ALWAYS design mobile AND desktop. Even if "it's a desktop app" —
   someone will open it on their phone.

5. ALWAYS fill design gaps rather than leaving them open.
   Log every gap filled in the Design Decisions Log.
   If the user disagrees with a gap decision, change it — but never leave it unspecified.

6. NEVER assume the color scheme, typography, or component library.
   Always ask in Round 1.

7. ALWAYS produce the implementation handoff checklist.
   Frontend can't implement what the spec doesn't specify.

8. The designer's job ends when the Frontend Architect says "I have everything I need."
   Not before.
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## AUTO-INJECT: Design runs in EVERY Workflow: with UI

The Design: trigger (and its interview protocol) is automatically part of
every Workflow: task that has user-facing screens. It is NOT optional.

Workflow: triggers that ALWAYS include Design: phase:
  → Any new page or route
  → Any new modal, drawer, or dialog
  → Any new form or multi-step flow
  → Any dashboard, list, or data table
  → Any onboarding or settings screen
  → Any error page or empty state
  → Any navigation change (new nav items, new sidebar sections)

Workflow: triggers that SKIP Design: phase:
  → Pure API endpoint work (no UI at all)
  → Background jobs or workers
  → Database migrations only
  → DevOps / infrastructure work

When in doubt: include Design:. A 10-minute design conversation prevents
hours of frontend rework.
